Vehicle Classification¶

Data Description:¶

The data contains features extracted from the silhouette of vehicles in different angles. Four "Corgie" model vehicles were used for the experiment: a double decker bus,Cheverolet van, Saab 9000 and an Opel Manta 400 cars.
This particular combination of vehicles was chosen with the expectation that the bus, van and either one of the cars would be readily distinguishable, but it would be more difficult to distinguish between the cars.

Domain:¶

Object recognition

Context:¶

The purpose is to classify a given silhouette as one of three types of vehicle, using a set of features extracted from the silhouette. The vehicle may be viewed from one of many different angles.

Objective:¶

Apply dimensionality reduction technique PCA and train a model using principle components instead of training the model using just the raw data.

Steps:¶

1. Data pre-processing – Perform all the necessary preprocessing¶

d. Dealing with outliers.¶

In [8]:
# we define outliers by using Inter Quantile range. 
# Data_point > (Q3 * 1.5) is said to be outlier where Q3 is 75% Quantile !

# finding the IQR for each of the numerical columns
def check_outliers():
    vData_num = vData.loc[:,vData.columns != 'class']
    Q1 = vData_num.quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = vData_num.quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    count = 0
    # checking for outliers, True represents outlier
    vData_num_mod = ((vData_num < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) |(vData_num > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR)))
    #iterating over columns to check for no.of outliers in each of the numerical attributes.
    for col in vData_num_mod:
        if(1 in vData_num_mod[col].value_counts().index):
            print("No. of outliers in %s: %d" %( col, vData_num_mod[col].value_counts().iloc[1]))
            count += 1
    print("\n\nNo of attributes with outliers are :", count)
    
check_outliers()

No. of outliers in max.length_aspect_ratio: 13
No. of outliers in scaled_variance: 1

Deductions:¶

  • We notice there a 8 attributes which have outliers.
  • Also,the no.of outliers are very low(< 20) w.r.t the total datapoints (846).
  • Hence, we will replace them with the median of the respective attributes.
In [9]:
# to replace with median we will loop through each column in the dataframe

for col in vData.columns[:-1]:
    Q1 = vData[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = vData[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_value = Q1 - (1.5 * IQR)
    upper_value = Q3 + (1.5 * IQR)
    
    vData.loc[(vData[col]< lower_value) | ( vData[col] > upper_value), col] = vData[col].median()

# check for outliers
check_outliers()


No of attributes with outliers are : 0

The data is now ready for model training, with no missing values or outliers.¶

Deductions:¶

  • 4 attributes 'pr.axis_aspect_ratio','max.length_aspect_ratio', 'skewness_about' and 'skewness_about.1' have very low correlation with other attributes. Hence these attributes can be directly considered for modelling.
  • We see many attributes are higly correclated with more than 0.9. Ex: 'scatter_ratio' and 'scaled variance' have a correlation of 0.98. Hence in such cases we can drop one of the attribute.

  • Also, seen many attributes have corr of greater than 0.7. Hence it would be difficult for us to deciede which ones to drop. Hence we go for PCA to determine the attributes to retain.

  • Attributes to consider for PCA = 14 (4 attributes left out based on point 1)

model = GridSearchCV(svm.SVC(), param_grid=params, verbose=1)
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# confidence intervals

lower = max(0.0, np.percentile(results, p))

upper = min(1.0, np.percentile(results, p))


print('%.1f confidence interval %.1f%% and %.1f%%' % (alpha*100, lower*100, upper*100))

# confidence intervals
alpha = 0.95                             # for 95% confidence 

p = ((1.0-alpha)/2.0) * 100              
lower = max(0.0, np.percentile(results, p))  

p = (alpha+((1.0-alpha)/2.0)) * 100
upper = min(1.0, np.percentile(results, p))


print('%.1f confidence interval %.1f%% and %.1f%%' % (alpha*100, lower*100, upper*100))

Deductions:¶

    Since, accuracy has not dropped substancially, we can consider SVM tuned using PCA to be the best model for this case.
